@nidhitewarilcsw is a licensed social worker who helps others process trauma and anxiety. She’s my guest on this live stream.

We talk about imposter syndrome, critique strategies and the anxiety we feel before important events.

She’ll be speaking to the #futurpro community on weds at 8am PDT. If you are interested in joining us, dm me the word “Pro” to get more information.

#mentalhealthsupport #impostersyndrome #limitingbeliefs #limitingbelief #negativeselftalk #affirmationsoftheday

Recently I was on the Millionaire Secrets podcast with @jefflernerofficial. We got into a fascinating and critical discussion as to why most creatives, designers (and entrepreneurs in general) will always struggle...
​​
​​...and never truly hit the big time. You can watch the full video on Jeff’s YouTube channel or on his podcast. Link in bio.

Content creation or content marketing can feel like a chore to do if you’re a creative. But it doesn’t have to be.

Learn how to repurpose your content and be omnipresent on social media with this helpful guide from @chykalophia. Follow them for more tips like this.

In case you haven’t noticed, I’ve spent a lot of time hosting rooms on #Clubhouse giving my team hours of material to work with for podcasts, blog posts, #reels and #shorts. What’s your content marketing strategy? Is it working for you?

Just wanted to give you a peek into my world and include a few of the books that help to shape my thinking. Now before your head explodes, I have not read all of the books. Not even close.

If it’s a good month for me, I’ll read 3-5 books, which works out to be about 48 books a year.

It’s not about consumption. It’s about retention. It’s not about retention, it’s about application. So it’s better to read 1 book and apply what you learn than to read all the books and do nothing.

About the space…
It’s a fairly tight room considering how much content I create which includes: YouTube, Clubhouse, Twitter, Instagram, LinkedIn, Futur Pro Zoom calls, virtual talks and podcasts. Everything here is either essential for work or makes me happy.

As a full-time content creator, former designer, and director, I pay careful attention to the tools that I use in my daily life. Every piece of equipment I use is highly attuned for my specific needs and a balance of: performance, ergonomics, aesthetics, build-quality, and general ease of use. I create an insane amount of daily content, so I don’t leave anything to chance.

I get a lot of questions about what my workstation/home office setup is like. Here’s the breakdown: Apple iMac Pro, Logitech MX KEYS keyboard, MX Master 3 mouse, Zone 3 wireless headphones, Blue Baby Bottle Mic, Blackmagic ATEM mini, Rodecaster Pro, M-Audio speakers, BenQ secondary display, Sony FS5 camera, Ikan teleprompter, Intuous Pro, Elgato Stream Deck and Aputure 120d w/ Lightdome.

What is one piece of kit you can’t live without in your office setup?
